### Pattern B: World-Building Staged Reveal

**When to use:** Brand storytelling, exploration-themed sites, adventure brands, map/geography concepts, any site where the homepage IS the brand world.

**Core principle:** The loader and the hero are the same world in different states of focus. The user watches the world resolve, not a loading bar complete.

**Motion rules:**
1. Start with the final world already designed, then put the intro state in an earlier stage of that same world
2. Reveal by expanding scale, mask area, visible element count, and layer opacity simultaneously
3. Let foreground UI and labels settle last — the page should feel like it has landed
4. Use decelerating curves throughout — `power2.out`, `power3.out`, or a cinematic custom bezier
5. Keep palette and motifs consistent between intro and hero for continuity

**HTML structure:**
```tsx
function WorldReveal() {
  return (
    <div className="relative w-screen h-screen overflow-hidden">
      {/* Atmosphere layer (canvas or video) */}
      <canvas className="absolute inset-0 w-full h-full" />

      {/* Preload overlay — same visual world, earlier state */}
      <div className="preload-overlay absolute inset-0 z-20 flex items-center justify-center bg-[#f5f5f0]">
        <div className="space-y-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-[#a3e635]">
          <p>System initializing</p>
          <p>Assets resolving</p>
          <p>World ready</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      {/* World layers */}
      <div className="world-terrain absolute inset-0" />
      <svg className="world-routes absolute inset-0 w-full h-full" />
      <div className="world-grid absolute inset-0 [background-image:linear-gradient(to_right,rgba(255,255,255,0.05)_1px,transparent_1px),linear-gradient(to_bottom,rgba(255,255,255,0.05)_1px,transparent_1px)] [background-size:100px_100px]" />

      {/* Hero CTA */}
      <h1 className="world-cta absolute bottom-12 left-1/2 -translate-x-1/2 text-[#a3e635] text-sm uppercase tracking-[0.2em]">
        Scroll to enter
      </h1>
    </div>
  )
}
```

